{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the handoff between file discovery/parsing/sorting and execution order against the DB. A unit test of the sorter can miss real miswiring (e.g., unsorted list consumed by executor). No OS/subprocess requirement, no LLM dependency.","test_description":"Use a temp `migrations/` directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., `010_b.sql`, `002_a.sql`, `100_c.sql`) and a local Postgres test DB. Each migration inserts its version into a probe table. Run the runner once, then assert probe rows reflect execution order `2,10,100` and `_migrations` records the same ordered versions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure depends on persisted state interaction between `_migrations` metadata and migration execution on later runs. Unit tests on skip logic alone can miss DB/state wiring defects. No subprocess/OS requirement.","test_description":"Create one migration that performs a non-idempotent effect (e.g., insert a unique row or increment counter once). Run runner twice against same local Postgres DB. Assert `_migrations` has one record for that version and effect happened only once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior relies on real transaction semantics plus runner control flow ac